AB  - Shrimp farming poses a significant challenge to agriculture in coastal Bangladesh, compounded by climate change and natural disasters. Therefore, the study aims to assess the impact of shrimp farming on food security among marginal farmers using Structural Equation Modeling (SEM). Additionally, we investigate scenarios of agriculture land conversion (1990-2022) in the southwestern coastal regions of Bangladesh through remote sensing techniques. To achieve the study objectives, we collected 672 respondents' opinions from the study regions through a self-administered questionnaire survey. The results indicate that a majority (60%) of the participants believe that rice yields have significantly decreased on their farms in the past ten years, with 70% attributing this decline to increased shrimp cultivation. SEM reveals that shrimp farming has a significant negative impact on farmers' income and dietary habits. Land use and land cover analyses indicate that the area dedicated to aquaculture has nearly doubled from 391.37 km2 in 1990 to 739.93 km2 in 2022.In contrast, agricultural land has decreased by 321.83 km2 over more than thirty years. Our analysis demonstrates that shrimp farming negatively impacts traditional agricultural practices and the sustainability of coastal agriculture by increasing soil salinity, thereby impacting marginalized farmers' food security through income reduction. This study provides valuable insights for policymakers worldwide to implement appropriate laws and regulations to control unplanned shrimp aquaculture in different coastal settings, thus contributing to sustainable development goals and food sovereignty.
