KW  - LIVESTOCK
KW  - ADOPTION
KW  - WEATHER
AB  - Climate change adaptation is critical for sustainable livestock production and securing the livelihoods of herder households. However, the effectiveness of current adaptation strategies and their influence on pastoral community welfare remain insufficiently explored. This research investigates the factors influencing herder households' decisions to adopt different adaptation strategies, focusing on why some prioritize traditional nomadicrotational grazing while others turn to engineering solutions. Utilizing an endogenous switching regression model with a control function approach and maximum likelihood estimation to address selection bias and heterogeneity in adaptation decisions. Data were collected from 830 herder households across six counties in Inner Mongolia and Gansu Province. The findings indicate that approximately 41 % of herder households practice nomadic-rotational grazing, while 54 % employ engineering adaptations. The propensity for nomadicrotational grazing is associated with cooler conditions and greater pasture access, whereas engineering adaptations are preferred in warmer, more humid conditions and among households situated closer to towns offering better access to government services. However, these adaptations are associated with a reduction in the household's income. The results highlight the complexity of adaptation decisions and underscore the need for the context-appropriate strategies that strengthen resilience without compromising economic well-being. A deeper understanding of these dynamics can inform more effective pastoral development policies and guide future research on refining adaptation measures to improve herder livelihoods under a changing climate.
