AB  - Nomadic communities are facing the adverse impact of climate change worldwide. In this context, this study quantifies the impact of climate change on the livelihoods of nomadic herders (N = 235) in the Western Himalayas (Jammu and Kashmir) in India. Nomads in this region are experiencing a reduction in perception and rising temperature, resulting in a decrease in the growth of pasture, a decrease in the quality and quantity of pasture, more weedy plants, reduced harvesting time of pasture, drying of sources of water, changing seasons, unstable weather, and reduced grazing areas. This study reveals that climate change has forced the nomadic herders to migrate early, which makes them face difficulties, such as ice cover over mountain passes, absence of pasture along the paths, unexpected avalanches, thunderstorms or hailstorms, and intense rain on the way to the uplands. Furthermore, this creates significant challenges for herders raising livestock. Less water availability and increased environmental disease risk are causing starvation and death of animals; a decrease in the quality and quantity of milk, wool, and meat; and lowering of the market price of final goods. Finally, this study brings to the attention of policymakers, climatologists, local governments, and animal health departments that climate change is endangering the lives of nomadic herders and that appropriate plans should be developed to minimise this loss.
