AB  - Climate change threatens and significantly affects agricultural activities through various mechanisms. One crucial factor is the temperature, which, when exceeding a specific threshold, adversely impacts harvests due to the accelerated pace of plant development. The primary objective of this study is to evaluate the impact of agricultural land, fertiliser inputs per unit of agricultural land, rainfall and temperature on cereal yields in Pakistan using annual data series. Utilizing the Quantile Autoregressive Distributed Lag (QARDL) methodology, we explore the interconnections among these variables in both the short and long-run. The study's findings show that agricultural land dedicated to crop cultivation across various quantiles has a positive impact on cereal yields in both the short and long term. The usage of fertiliser inputs per unit of agricultural land improves cereal yields in the short and long run. However, the effectiveness of this method decreases as the quantiles increase. Furthermore, it has been shown that, over the time, a decrease in cereal yields is connected with low to moderate levels of rainfall, while the influence of rainfall at higher quantiles is insignificant. The effect of temperature on cereal yields in Pakistan varies depending on the temperature level and prevailing circumstances. The study's results suggest a variety of strategies to increase crop yields, including increasing agricultural production, enhancing land utilization and improving farmer access to funding.
